{\"video_title\": \"Ask for Input Pattern | Coursera\", \"transcript\": \"вЂ‹When we're working with large language models, вЂ‹often we're going to describe in our prompt a set вЂ‹of rules that we want the large language model to follow. вЂ‹Rules that are going to affect its output вЂ‹and essentially program the large language model. вЂ‹One of the things that we're going to want to вЂ‹do, we're going to want to say, вЂ‹here are the rules, вЂ‹now apply them to вЂ‹an input that I'm going to provide later. вЂ‹One of the challenges is, вЂ‹how do we get the large language model not вЂ‹to immediately respond to all of our rules? вЂ‹If we have a flipped interaction, for example, вЂ‹sometimes when we flip the interaction and we say, вЂ‹ask us questions, it'll generate вЂ‹10 or 20 questions all at once. вЂ‹A way to do is basically a simple way that вЂ‹we can get the large language model вЂ‹to listen to what we're saying, вЂ‹acknowledge it, and then wait for input from us. вЂ‹Now, we can do this with the ask for input pattern. вЂ‹The idea behind this is we want to get вЂ‹the large language model to listen to вЂ‹the rules and then ask us вЂ‹for the input to apply the rules to. вЂ‹When we're talking about вЂ‹asking questions in a flipped interaction, вЂ‹we might want to describe вЂ‹the rules for asking the question, вЂ‹and then we just wanted to ask one question. вЂ‹So we just want to get one question out. вЂ‹If we're describing rules for alternative approaches, вЂ‹we might want to say, here are the rules. вЂ‹You're always going to create alternative approaches вЂ‹to whatever asked you to do, вЂ‹but just ask me now for вЂ‹the first task to create alternative approaches for, вЂ‹we don't want you to go and have a big response to it. вЂ‹What we see is that that's not always the case. вЂ‹Let's take a look at this example. вЂ‹Now, in a prior video, вЂ‹I introduced the alternative approaches pattern, вЂ‹and when you saw me use this pattern, вЂ‹it worked really effectively because I was actually вЂ‹combining it with the ask for input pattern. вЂ‹I'm going to show you what it looks like when I вЂ‹don't combine it with the ask for input pattern. вЂ‹I went and I said, вЂ‹whenever I ask you to write вЂ‹a prompt for me to accomplish a task, вЂ‹list what the task is, вЂ‹list the alternative approaches for creating the task, вЂ‹and then write a prompt for yourself for each approach. вЂ‹I'm asking in ChatGPT, вЂ‹give me a bunch of alternatives for prompting you, вЂ‹ChatGPT, to solve the task. вЂ‹This is going back to the earlier idea вЂ‹where I showed how we can actually use вЂ‹ChatGPT to generate prompts вЂ‹for itself to help us with prompt engineering. вЂ‹What I do is I use this, вЂ‹but I'm taking away something вЂ‹important that I'm going to show you in a minute. вЂ‹What it does is ChatGPT responds, вЂ‹it says certainly, but then it dreams up a task. вЂ‹It says, here are three alternatives for completing вЂ‹the task organizing a cluttered desk. вЂ‹I'm not interested in вЂ‹the task organized a cluttered desk. вЂ‹It just responded to my initial prompt, вЂ‹which was, create alternative approaches for a task. вЂ‹It dreamed up a task and then dreamed up вЂ‹its own approaches for that task. вЂ‹Now, I'm not interested in this, вЂ‹so now I've got my conversation and it's got вЂ‹all this extra stuff in it that I don't care about. вЂ‹I had to wait for it to generate it. вЂ‹If I was trying to create вЂ‹some interactive experience that had some consistency, вЂ‹this would not be helpful. вЂ‹What I can do is I can apply the ask for input pattern. вЂ‹Then the idea behind this is вЂ‹we just do one simple thing, вЂ‹and at the end of the prompt, вЂ‹we tell the large language model вЂ‹to ask for the next input. вЂ‹In this case we say, ask me for the first task. вЂ‹The very last thing we do, вЂ‹we describe all the rules, вЂ‹or whatever it is that we want in our prompt, вЂ‹and then the last thing we do is we say, now, вЂ‹ask me for the first task, вЂ‹ask me for the first idea, вЂ‹ask me for the first thing you want вЂ‹me to generate a story about, whatever it is. вЂ‹But it's a way that we can cut вЂ‹off the large language model and tell it, вЂ‹don't go generate a bunch of stuff. вЂ‹I'm glad that you can do that, вЂ‹but what I want you to do is I want you to stop right вЂ‹here and asked me what I want to do. вЂ‹It's a way of forcing вЂ‹the large language model to basically вЂ‹turn the control back over to вЂ‹the user and let them decide what to do next. вЂ‹Now, like all prompt patterns, вЂ‹when we're dealing with a larger language model, вЂ‹it is somewhat stochastic or random. вЂ‹It means it's not always going to do вЂ‹exactly the same thing every time. вЂ‹It may not work 100 percent of the time, вЂ‹but this works very, very reliably to just say, вЂ‹ask me for the first input or вЂ‹whatever it is at the end of вЂ‹the prompt because it вЂ‹clues the large language model and it needs to stop. вЂ‹If we look at the comparison of the output, вЂ‹it's actually much more focused. вЂ‹We see, in this case it says, вЂ‹certainly, let's begin. вЂ‹What is the first task you would like me to create вЂ‹alternative approaches and prompts for? вЂ‹Rather than this much longer saying that it generated вЂ‹before that was not вЂ‹really helpful to what we were doing, вЂ‹so it cuts it off. вЂ‹Notice it's the same input, вЂ‹but it cut it off. вЂ‹It's told that, look, you need to вЂ‹stop right here and you вЂ‹need to wait for my input.\"} 